Travel to Ireland is subject to entry restrictions. Please refer to Irish Government travel guidance before you travel from Great Britain to Ireland
Up to 19 July:
Travellers to Ireland must fill out a Passenger Locator Form. Failure to complete this form is an offence
All passengers are required to have a negative pre-departure Reverse Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction (RT-PCR) Covid-19 test taken within 72 hours prior to arrival in Ireland. Antigen or other test types do not meet the requirement. Arriving in Ireland without evidence of a negative/‘not-detected’ test result is an offence
Children between the ages of 7 and 17 travelling to Ireland must have a negative RT-PCR test, even when accompanied by fully vaccinated or recovered adults. Children aged 6 and under do not need to take a RT-PCR test prior to travelling to Ireland.
All passengers travelling from Great Britain to Ireland must quarantine at home for 14 days. This is a legal requirement, with limited exceptions. The period of home quarantine can be shortened following a negative PCR test after 5 days – see Irish Government guidance on how to book your free PCR test
Travellers whose journey originates in Northern Ireland are outside the scope of quarantine schemes unless they have been overseas during the 14 days prior to arrival in Ireland.
From 19 July, Ireland entry requirements will change
All travellers to Ireland will need to fill out a Passenger Locator Form. Failure to complete this form is an offence.
No travel-related testing or quarantine will be necessary for travellers from Great Britain with valid proof of full vaccination.
If you do not have valid proof of vaccination and are travelling from Great Britain you will need to:
present evidence of a negative RT-PCR test result within 72 hours prior to arrival into the country
self-quarantine
undergo post-arrival testing
Travellers should note that guidance can change at short notice and check Irish Government advice before they travel
See Entry requirements for more information before you plan to travel.
For information about COVID-19 vaccines, see the Coronavirus page.
Around 3 million British nationals visit Ireland each year. Most visits are trouble free.
You should carry an acceptable form of photo-identification to travel between the UK and Ireland. See Entry requirements
Terrorist attacks in Ireland can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
If you’re living in or moving to Ireland, visit our Living in Ireland guide in addition to this travel advice.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
